Imagine this scenario: you are working at a startup in NYC after graduating from Tufts. You are inevitably overworked managing agentic AI solutions and are therefore sleep deprived. Every day, you catch the subway to work, and waste precious sleep time waiting for it at the station. What if there was a way for you to know when the train was arriving at your local station from the comfort of your bedroom? That would be great, wouldn’t it? You could sleep in and ensure that you don’t miss your train.

Look no further than our EE 14 final project. For this project, we will consume real-time data (that is used by the MTA!) and transform the payload into a simplified structure. We will translate this structure on an ESP32 into pixels on an LED Matrix display, similar to the display board on subway platforms. Of course, the subway system is huge, and not everyone needs the status on the same stop or the same line. So, we have an STM32 that is in charge of responding to user input directly from a programmable joystick. The user will then be able to see their line and station configurations using an OLED display. By combining all these components, we hope to provide an affordable, convenient tool for New York City residents as they go about their morning routines. 

